name: Brian Calley
tweet: Herd immunity through vaccinations is a race. This aggressive approach means we will be much more likely to be at a maximum pace the whole way through. Smart plan by the Governor and her team on this. 8/8

name: Brian Calley
tweet: Right now, anyone over 65 knows, they need to get signed up and on the list before the 50-64 year olds start on March 22nd. And the 50-64 year olds know that they only have 2 weeks to get signed up before the 16-49 year olds come. 7/

name: Brian Calley
tweet: Two weeks later, anyone over 16 will be eligible (as of April 5th). It might seem strange to announce such widely expanded eligibility criteria ahead of vaccine supply, but I believe predetermining the next big steps creates motivation and urgency. 6/

name: Brian Calley
tweet: Returning to a focus on age will improve the efficiency & pace of the systems and prioritize those with the highest risk of serious illness/death. Over 50 with preexisting conditions get a head start before March 22 when everyone over 50 is eligible. 5/

name: Brian Calley
tweet: When the state originally opened eligibility up to everyone over 65, it moved us up the ranks in efficiency in distribution because it was a simple eligibility criteria and there was huge demand driving every distribution channel to perform. 4/

name: Brian Calley
tweet: No matter how determined people in charge of government distribution are, the system will take as much time as you give it. Expanding eligibility beyond capacity is the best way to ensure that the system is doing as much and moving as fast as it possibly can. 3/

name: Brian Calley
tweet: The federal mass vaccination site is a good opportunity, but the continuation of pushing supply, distribution and administration by aggressively expanding eligibility is the key development. Here‚Äôs what I love about this approach... 2/
